Yes, it is thread-safe to read from a single channel in multiple go routines in Golang. The go routines will synchronize on the channel, ensuring that only one go routine will receive a value at a time. This is one of the core design principles of Go's concurrency model, and channels are designed with built-in synchronization mechanisms to enable safe communication between go routines.

Here's an example illustrating multiple go routines reading from a single channel:

```go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "sync"
)

func main() {
    ch := make(chan int, 10)

    go func() {
        for i := 0; i < 10; i++ {
            ch <- i
        }
        close(ch)
    }()

    var wg sync.WaitGroup
    wg.Add(3)

    for i := 1; i <= 3; i++ {
        go func(id int) {
            defer wg.Done()
            for v := range ch {
                fmt.Printf("Go routine %d received value: %d\n", id, v)
            }
        }(i)
    }

    wg.Wait()
}
```

In this example, there are three go routines reading from the same channel `ch`, and the channel is meant for communication between the main go routine and the three other go routines. The `sync.WaitGroup` is used to make sure the main go routine waits for all other go routines to finish before exiting.

Keep in mind, when multiple go routines read from a single channel, the order in which they read might not be deterministic, so you might get different orders of output each time you run the program.

To create a clean architecture project called "filelynk" using Golang, PostgreSQL, and GORM, you'll want to separate your code into three main layers: domain, repository, and service.

Here's a possible directory structure and some sample code to help you get started:

```
filelynk/
  cmd/
    main.go
  domain/
    entities.go
  repository/
    user.go
    file.go
    plan.go
    userplan.go
  service/
    user.go
    file.go
    plan.go
  config/
    config.go
  internal/
    postgre.go
```

1. `cmd/main.go` - This is the entry point of the application:

```go
package main

import (
	"filelynk/config"
	"filelynk/internal"
	"filelynk/repository"
	"filelynk/service"
	"fmt"
)

func main() {
	// Load configuration
	config.Load()

	// Initialize database connection
	db, err := internal.ConnectPostgreSQL()
	if err != nil {
		fmt.Println("Failed to connect to the database:", err)
		return
	}
	defer db.Close()

	// Initialize repositories
	userRepo := repository.NewUserRepository(db)
	fileRepo := repository.NewFileRepository(db)
	planRepo := repository.NewPlanRepository(db)
	userPlanRepo := repository.NewUserPlanRepository(db)

	// Initialize services
	userService := service.NewUserService(userRepo)
	fileService := service.NewFileService(fileRepo, userPlanRepo)
	planService := service.NewPlanService(planRepo)

	// Application logic goes here, e.g., HTTP server, user registration & authentication, etc.
}
```

2. `domain/entities.go` - This file holds your entities (structs):

```go
