In Yew, a Rust framework for building web applications, you can route messages between components independently of where they sit in the component hierarchy by using "agents." Agents are special components that can communicate with other components without sharing the same parent or ancestor.

Here's a step-by-step guide on how to use agents in Yew:

1. Create an Agent.
To create an agent, you need a new struct that will implement the `Agent` trait. Here's an example:

```rust
use yew::agent::{Agent, Context, HandlerId};

pub struct MessageAgent {
    subscribers: Vec<HandlerId>,
}

impl Agent for MessageAgent {
    type Reach = Context<Self>;
    type Message = ();
    type Input = String;
    type Output = String;

    fn create(_link: Link<Self>) -> Self {
        Self { subscribers: vec![] }
    }

    fn update(&mut self, _msg: Self::Message) {}

    fn handle_input(&mut self, input: Self::Input, _id: HandlerId) {
        for subscriber in self.subscribers.iter() {
            self.send_message(subscriber.clone(), input.clone());
        }
    }

    fn connected(&mut self, id: HandlerId) {
        self.subscribers.push(id);
    }

    fn disconnected(&mut self, id: HandlerId) {
        self.subscribers.retain(|subscriber| *subscriber != id);
    }
}
```

2. Registering and using the agent in components.
Now that you've created your agent, you can use it in components to route messages. You need to register the agent and bridge a connection.

Here's an example of a component called `SenderComponent` that sends messages to the agent:

```rust
use yew::{prelude::*, Component, ComponentLink};
use yew::agent::Bridged;

pub struct SenderComponent {
    link: ComponentLink<Self>,
    message_agent: Box<dyn yew::agent::Bridge<MessageAgent>>,
}

impl SenderComponent {
    fn send_message(&mut self) {
        self.message_agent.send(format!("Hello!"));
    }
}

impl Component for SenderComponent {
    type Message = ();
    type Properties = ();

    fn create(_ctx: &Context<Self>) -> Self {
        let callback = |_| ();
        let mut message_agent = MessageAgent::bridge(callback);
        Self {
            link: ComponentLink::new(),
            message_agent,
        }
    }

    fn update(&mut self, _: Self::Message) -> ShouldRender {
        false
    }

    fn view(&self) -> Html {
        html! {
            <button onclick=self.link.callback(|_| self.send_message())>{ "Send Message" }</button>
        }
    }
}
```

And here's an example of a component called `ReceiverComponent` that receives messages from the agent:

```rust
use yew::{prelude::*, Component, ComponentLink};
use yew::agent::Bridged;

pub struct ReceiverComponent {
    received_msg: Option<String>,
    message_agent: Box<dyn yew::agent::Bridge<MessageAgent>>,
}

impl Component for ReceiverComponent {
    type Message = String;
    type Properties = ();

    fn create(_ctx: &Context<Self>) -> Self {
        let callback = Self::Message::from;
        let message_agent = MessageAgent::bridge(callback);
        Self {
            received_msg: None,
            message_agent,
        }
    }

    fn update(&mut self, msg: Self::Message) -> ShouldRender {
        self.received_msg = Some(msg);
        true
    }

    fn view(&self) -> Html {
        if let Some(ref message) = self.received_msg {
            html! {
                <div>{ format!("Received message: {}", message) }</div>
            }
        } else {
            html! {
                <div>{ "No messages received" }</div>
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Now you have two components that can exchange messages through the `MessageAgent` independently of where they sit in the component hierarchy.

3. Finally, add the components to the main view.

```rust
pub fn main() {
    yew::start_app::<ParentComponent>();
}

pub struct ParentComponent;

impl Component for ParentComponent {
    type Message = ();
    type Properties = ();

    fn create(_ctx: &Context<Self>) -> Self {
        Self
    }

    fn update(&mut self, _msg: Self::Message) -> ShouldRender {
        false
    }

    fn view(&self) -> Html {
        html! {
            <>
                <SenderComponent />
                <ReceiverComponent />
            </>
        }
    }
}
```

With these changes, you have successfully implemented message routing between components using Yew's agents. The `SenderComponent` sends a message, the `MessageAgent` receives it and broadcasts it to all interested subscribers, and the `ReceiverComponent` receives and displays the message.

