The crucial part here is setting the HTTP headers to simulate a web browser that is interacting with the server. We're setting common headers used by most modern browsers, but we also add some headers that are specific to Google search, like the "Referer", "authority", and "upgrade-insecure-requests" headers.

These headers tell Google search that our program is behaving like a web browser and interacting with the server in a way that is similar to how a human user would do it. By setting these headers, we make it less likely that our program will be identified as a robot and blocked by the server.

Overall, the code to behave like a browser on Google search is similar to the code used for Bing search, but it requires some additional headers and customization to avoid being blocked by Google's more sophisticated anti-scraping measures.

Adding the appropriate HTTP headers to scrape DuckDuckGo search results is similar to adding them for Bing and Google, but with some small differences.

Here is an example of Java code that adds the appropriate HTTP headers to behave like a browser for DuckDuckGo search:

```
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;
import java.net.HttpURLConnection;
import java.net.URL;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class DuckDuckGoSearch {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        HashMap<Integer, String> results = new HashMap<>();
        String query = "house";
        String source = "https://duckduckgo.com/html/?q=" + query;

        URL url = new URL(source);
        HttpURLConnection con = (HttpURLConnection) url.openConnection();

        // Set HTTP headers
        Map<String, String> headers = new HashMap<>();
        headers.put("User-Agent", "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/58.0.3029.110 Safari/537.36");
        headers.put("Accept-Language", "en-US,en;q=0.5");
        headers.put("Accept-Encoding", "gzip, deflate, br");
        headers.put("Connection", "keep-alive");
        headers.put("Referer", "https://duckduckgo.com/");
        headers.put("Host", "duckduckgo.com");

        for (String key : headers.keySet()) {
            con.setRequestProperty(key, headers.get(key));
        }

        BufferedReader in = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(con.getInputStream()));
        String inputLine;

        int count = 1;
        while ((inputLine = in.readLine()) != null && count <= 10) {
            if (inputLine.contains("https://")) {
                String[] strArr = inputLine.split("\"");
                for (String str : strArr) {
                    if (str.contains("https://")) {
                        results.put(count, str);
                        count++;
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        in.close();

        System.out.println("First 10 'https url' search results for the query '" + query + "' are:");
        for (int key : results.keySet()) {
            System.out.println(key + "." + results.get(key));
        }

    }

}
```

The key lines of code in this example are again the ones where we create a Map with the desired headers and set them in the HTTP request. In this case, we're setting common headers used by most modern browsers, such as User-Agent, Accept-Language, Accept-Encoding, Connection, and Referer. Additionally, we set the "Host" header to indicate that the request is going to the DuckDuckGo server.

By setting these headers, we're telling DuckDuckGo that our program is behaving like a web browser. This will allow us to parse search results without getting rejected or blocked.

Please note that the HTML structure of the search results page may vary from one search engine to another. Therefore, the way you extract the URLs from the page source may be different based on the specific HTML structure and how the URLs are presented.

